-- Hong Kong shares close at 3-week high on property, banking gains
-- By Natalie Thomas
-- Wed May 14, 2014 04:08AM EDT
-- None



BEIJING, May 14 (Reuters) - Hong Kong shares hit a three-week high on Wednesday, as property and banking stocks continued to rise after China's central bank urged mainland lenders to speed up the granting of home loans.

The Hang Seng Index <.HSI> ended up 1.0 percent at 22,582.77 points, its highest close since April 22. The China Enterprises Index <.HSCE> of the leading offshore Chinese listings in Hong Kong was up 1.4 percent.  China's central bank asked commercial banks on Monday to speed up the granting of home loans and to set mortgage rates at reasonable levels, in a bid to stabilise the mainland's increasingly wobbly housing market. [ID:nL3N0NZ1PJ] China Overseas Land & Investment Ltd <0688.HK> jumped 4.1 percent and China Resources Land Ltd <1109.HK> gained 6.0 percent. The Hang Seng property index <.HSNP> was up 1.8 percent.